Lagos – The Golden Eaglets of Nigeria have an uphill task to scale in the qualifiers for the 2019 Africa U-17 Cup of Nations billed for Tanzania from May 12 to 26, 2019. SATURDAY INDEPENDENT gathered that the Eaglets, who could not qualify for the last edition of the competition, will now have to scale past former FIFA U-17 World Cup winners, Ghana, and equally formidable Cote d’Ivoire in the qualifiers. This comes after the Confederation of African Football (CAF) redesigned the format of qualifying the cadet tournament, in which the eliminators will now be played on zonal basis and a final lap will be staged in Tanzania. Eaglets will have to first slug it out of their West African rivals, in CAF West B Zone, which has Cote d’Ivoire, Benin Republic, Niger Republic, Ghana, Togo and Burkina Faso. CAF revealed that Ghana will host the West B Zone qualifiers and Burundi will stage the Central-East Zone. The seven overall winners of the zonal qualifiers will advance automatically to join the hosts, Tanzania for the tournament proper next year. The qualifiers will kick off after the 2018 World Cup in Russia in June, with Nigeria looking to avoid a repeat of last time out, when the Golden Eaglets were eliminated by Niger Republic from making it to the 2017 Under-17 AFCON in Rwanda. Meanwhile, the first phase of screening for the new look Golden Eaglets ended on Friday (yesterday) in Abuja, after returnee coach, Manu Garba checked 50 invited players from last year’s National Under-15 Championship. 0 comments Do you get a good or bad response from your wife after making love? Discover a great natural solution that changed my story and put an end to weak/premature ejaculation, CLICK HERE.  100% Natural Solution To Premature Ejaculation, Weak Erection, Watery Sperm, Other Sexual Dysfunctions And Last More Than 30 Minutes During Sex.